<L N="440">The fortunes of the &s;l$cce; who&s;e ance&s;tors</L>
<L><PB N="80" REF="83">
Were fugitives from &s;uper&s;tition's rage,</L>
<L>And er&s;t from Devon, thither brought the loom;</L>
<L>Where ivy'd walls of old Kidwelly's tow'rs,</L>
<L>Nodding, &s;till on their gloomy brows project</L>
<L>Lanca&s;tria's arms, $mbo&s;s'd in mould'ring &s;tone.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>THUS then, on Albion's coa&s;t, the exil'd band,</L>
<L>From ri$h Men$pian towns, and the green banks</L>
<L>Of S$h$ld alig$$$d; and, alighting, &s;ang</L>
<L>Grateful thank&s;giving. Y$$, at times, they &s;hift</L>
<L N="450">Their habitations, when the hand of pride,</L>
<L>Re&s;traint, or &s;outhern luxury, di&s;turbs</L>
<L>Their indu&s;try, and urges them to vales</L>
<L>Of the Brigantes; where, with happier care</L>
<L>In&s;pirited, their art improves the &s;leece,</L>
<L>Which occupation er&s;t, and wealth immen&s;e,</L>
<L>Gave Brabant's &s;warming habitants, what time</L>
<L>We were their &s;hepherds only; from which &s;tate,</L>
<L>With friendly arm, they rais'd us: nathle&s;s &s;ome</L>
<L>Among our old and &s;tubborn &s;wains mi&s;deem'd,</L>
<L N="460">And envy'd, who enrich'd them; envy'd tho&s;e,</L>
<L>Who&s;e virtues taught the varl$try of towns</L>
