<HEAD>The ARGUMENT.</HEAD>
<P>Our manufactures exported. Voyage through the Channel, and by the Coa&s;t of Spain. View of the Mediterranean. D$cay of the Tur|key-trade. Addre&s;s to the factors there. Voyage through the Balti$. The mart of Petersburg. The ancient channels of commerce to the Indies. The modern cour&s;e thither. Shores of Afric. Refl$ctions on the &s;lave-trade. The Cape of Good Hope, and the $a&s;tern part of Afric. Trade to Per&s;ia and Indo&s;tan, pr$carious through tyranny and frequent in&s;urrections. Di&s;putes between the French and Engli&s;h, on the coa&s;t of Cormandel, cen&s;ured. A pro&s;pect of the Spice-i&s;lands, and of China. Traffic at Canton. Our woolen manufactures known at Pekin, by the caravans from Ru&s;&s;ia. De&s;cription of that journey. Tran&s;ition to the we&s;tern hemi&s;phere. Voyage of Raleigh. The &s;tate and advantages of our North American colonies. Severe winters in tho&s;e climates: hence the p$&s;&s;age through Hud&s;on's bay impracticable. Enquiries for an ea&s;ier pa&s;&s;age into the Pacific oc$an. View of the coa&s;ts of South America, and of tho&s;e tempe&s;tuous &s;eas. Lord An|&s;on's expedition, and &s;ucce&s;s again&s;t the Spaniards. The naval pow|er of $word$ con&s;i&s;tent with the welfare of all nations. View of our probable impr$$ements in traffic, and the di&s;tribution of our wo$ll$n manufactures over the whole globe.</P>
